“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors are patrolling the Navy headquarters in La Paz.
Navy blue flags are displayed on public buildings.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are covered with a slogan: “We have a right to the sea.
It is our duty to get it back.”
In mainland Bolivia, the memory of the loss of the coast in a bloody conflict over natural resources with Chile in the 19th century is still alive—as is the longing for a re-float of the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is perhaps the greatest in decades, as Bolivia awaits the international court's decision, which will be delivered on October 1 after five years of consultations.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and impartiality, and of course, in a positive spirit, it expects a result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the international court’s decision on big screens across the country, hoping that a court in The Hague will rule in Bolivia’s favor, arguing that, after decades of volatile talks, Chile must negotiate Bolivia’s access to sovereign access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has high expectations for Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe the court will not rule in Bolivia’s favor —and even if it did, it would not change much.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the power to allocate Chilean territory to Bolivia and will not decide on the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the international court’s decision comes just six months after hearing the final arguments means that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And for the past four years, they've not been talking in favor of Bolivia, but they're probably going to cost it a lot.
