Morales’ aggressive rhetoric has absorbed all the goodwill from the Chileans that may still be there, she explained.
Talks between Bolivia and Chile will continue at some point, but after that it will be extremely difficult to participate in the discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, the Bolivian representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court took a decision unusually quickly.
He said Monday would bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity for a new era of relations with Chile” and an opportunity to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits.”
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime issue as a political backing.
