John Edward: Knowledge of languages is crucial for global citizens
Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, further reinforced by individual and collective achievements in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and the city they have as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language that he understands, the conversation is imprinted in his memory.
But if you talk to a person in his or her native language, the words are imprinted on his or her heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the rankings with the highest success rates in independent schools.
68% of students who studied a foreign language achieved an excellent grade.
Data collected from 74 Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) member schools showed that 72% of pupils scored excellent in Mandarin, while 72% of German pupils, 69% of French pupils and 63% of Spanish pupils also scored excellent.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as an optional subject in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of science, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK’s Employment and Training Commission found that 17% of the reasons employers struggle to fill job vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
For future job opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in a global world.
If someone learns another language, whatever career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically has a competitive advantage.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, that is, 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for children today.
By knowing more languages, especially those from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding a suitable job.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are supposed to be most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your child, in independent schools it will always be possible to choose from a number of languages taught by specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must be expressed in education as well.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
