North Korea: 'Without confidence, we will not disarm unilaterally'
The North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued implementation of sanctions is causing growing mistrust of the United States and that North Korea will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the body that North Korea had taken a number of "significant goodwill measures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, undermining a nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“We don’t see the right response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, we will not be confident in national security, and under such conditions we will not unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea for adopting gradual measures, his statement was important because it did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the incumbent U.S. President and the North Korean leader, held on June 12 in Singapore. At the time, Kim pledged to strive for “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula”, while Trump promised North Korea Security assurances.
North Korea wants an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for the lifting of tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists that we must first disarm nuclear weapons, and it is escalating pressure with sanctions to coerce us into achieving our goals, and it is even opposing the declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions could bring us to our knees is the unrealistic hope of people who don’t know us at all.
The problem, however, is that the continued implementation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second Kim-Trump summit, which the US president outlined at the United Nations Assembly earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the problem of nuclear disarmament were discussed with South Korea rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have landed at such a dead end.”
However, the tone of Mr. Ri’s speech was completely different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that an attack on the U.S. mainland with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim “a missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said he still had a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no timetable for this, saying, “It could be two years, three years, or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia are of the opinion that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
On Thursday, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the United Nations Security Council: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue resolutely and without exception until we recognize a complete, final and verified state of nuclear disarmament.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions against North Korea to prevent funding for North Korea's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Rio on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not end well.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said that progress had been made, and a few hours later North Korea criticized him, saying his demands were “gangsteric.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to demolish a missile test station and nuclear test infrastructure if the United States takes "appropriate action".
Kim said the “appropriate measures” meant the security assurances Trump promised in Singapore and measures to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course to learn how to take enough time to rest
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is to teach all undergraduate students how to afford more sleep. With such a course, they want to fight against the growing macho culture of “all-night” learning, in which the forces are accumulated with caffeine.
The university professor found that the students of the world’s best university often do not know the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, designed the course, which is the first of its kind in the United States.
To carry out such a course, he decided after his lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to him and said, “Why do I only find out now that I’m in my senior year?”
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and the professor told The Daily Telegraph that he was surprised.
The course, which is being conducted for the first time this year, speaks about the key importance of good sleep habits for academic and sports success, as well as for improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, says they chose such a course when they found that students significantly lacked sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dorm door where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports slippers, and books to get information about the impact of caffeine and light, the impact of lack of sleep on athletic success, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In the second section, participants learn that prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart failure, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The map of the student settlement with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We are aware that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have a right to know these facts, just as they have a right to know how cigarette smoking affects their health,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The professor says that the culture of pride is still present with “survived night-long learning” and adds that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, resulting in lack of sleep, are growing problems.
Professor Czeisler says that a sufficient amount of quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety. Thus, they can also avoid weight gain – the brain, due to lack of sleep, goes into the mode of hunger, which makes students constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year, during his first year at Harvard, he attended one of the professor's lectures.
He says that the lecture opened his eyes and encouraged him to conduct a course throughout the student settlement.
He hopes to be able to ask postgraduate students to complete a similar study programme in the next phase before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock for sleeping as well as waking up. He also wants to alert them to the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic displays and LED lighting, as they can cause an imbalance in the circadian rhythm, which makes it difficult to fall asleep.
