Red tide news: Concentrations on the coasts of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa counties are decreasing
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) shows an overall decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC has reported more diffuse flowering in the Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier districts, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide extends approximately 130 miles from the coast of Pinellas County's north to Lee County's south.
The patches look about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also seen in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported in the Pinellas County and along its coast, low to high concentrations along the Hillsborough County coast, base to high concentrations in the Manatee County, base to high concentrations in the Saratosa County and along its coast, base to medium concentrations in the Leigh County, base to high concentrations in the Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
